00:51:13.966 --> 00:51:14.766 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Yeah.

00:51:14.766 --> 00:51:15.566 align:middle line:90%
I hear you.

00:51:15.566 --> 00:51:18.120 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So let's go ahead and
talk about the "Poughkeepsie

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:18.920 align:middle line:90%
Seer."

00:51:18.920 --> 00:51:20.890 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: Oh, one of
my favorite characters.

00:51:20.890 --> 00:51:23.220 align:middle line:84%
Now the Poughkeepsie
Seer was a young man

00:51:23.220 --> 00:51:25.710 align:middle line:84%
named Andrew Jackson
Davis who grew up

00:51:25.710 --> 00:51:27.960 align:middle line:84%
in the industrial town
of Poughkeepsie, which

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:30.090 align:middle line:84%
was in New York's
Hudson Valley, just

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:31.800 align:middle line:84%
adjacent to the
Burned-over district.

00:51:31.800 --> 00:51:34.710 align:middle line:84%
In many ways, it's
the Eastern border

00:51:34.710 --> 00:51:37.140 align:middle line:90%
of the Burned-over district.

00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:43.710 align:middle line:84%
Davis was the son of a local
ne'er-do-well sharecropper.

00:51:43.710 --> 00:51:46.530 align:middle line:84%
He was apprenticed
out to a cobbler.

00:51:46.530 --> 00:51:50.100 align:middle line:84%
And, in the early
1840s, he began

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:53.280 align:middle line:84%
to experiment with
mesmerism or what we today

00:51:53.280 --> 00:51:54.540 align:middle line:90%
would call hypnotism.

00:51:54.540 --> 00:51:56.137 align:middle line:84%
It was an occult
healing philosophy--

00:51:56.137 --> 00:51:56.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of Europe.

00:51:56.970 --> 00:51:58.428 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: --that
began in Europe,

00:51:58.428 --> 00:52:01.510 align:middle line:84%
crossed the Atlantic
to the Americas.

00:52:01.510 --> 00:52:06.000 align:middle line:84%
And Davis found that he
could go into these very

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:09.360 align:middle line:84%
deep mesmeric trances
or what we today

00:52:09.360 --> 00:52:11.430 align:middle line:90%
would call hypnotic trances.

00:52:11.430 --> 00:52:14.640 align:middle line:84%
And he would experience
these astral travels

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:18.120 align:middle line:84%
and out-of-body experiences
while he was in trance states.

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:21.150 align:middle line:84%
And he said he would travel to
other planets, and dimensions,

00:52:21.150 --> 00:52:22.774 align:middle line:90%
and visit with angels--

00:52:22.774 --> 00:52:23.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Heaven, all of it.

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:25.670 align:middle line:90%
--journey to the heavens.

00:52:25.670 --> 00:52:28.560 align:middle line:84%
And he would come
back, and he would

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:32.040 align:middle line:84%
give these metaphysical
lectures and treatises

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:35.820 align:middle line:84%
based on what he had experienced
when he was in a trance state.

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:39.210 align:middle line:84%
And he began to
grow in popularity.

00:52:39.210 --> 00:52:42.450 align:middle line:84%
He moved to New
York City in 1845.

00:52:42.450 --> 00:52:45.240 align:middle line:84%
And newspapers began
jokingly referring to him

00:52:45.240 --> 00:52:48.840 align:middle line:84%
as the "Poughkeepsie Seer,"
but he embraced the nickname,

00:52:48.840 --> 00:52:50.460 align:middle line:90%
and he would freely use it.

00:52:50.460 --> 00:52:54.010 align:middle line:84%
And Davis, for a period of
time, was a very, very popular

00:52:54.010 --> 00:52:54.810 align:middle line:90%
figure.

00:52:54.810 --> 00:52:56.670 align:middle line:84%
He attracted the
interest of Edgar Allan

00:52:56.670 --> 00:53:00.210 align:middle line:84%
Poe, with whom he was, I believe
the word today is frenemies.

00:53:00.210 --> 00:53:02.200 align:middle line:84%
They sort of
detested one another

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:04.320 align:middle line:84%
but also spent a lot
of time together.

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:08.100 align:middle line:84%
He also attracted the interest
of a Reverend George Bush

00:53:08.100 --> 00:53:11.280 align:middle line:84%
who was an ancestor to the
Bush presidential family.

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:13.140 align:middle line:84%
And he was a big
defender of Davis.

00:53:13.140 --> 00:53:16.590 align:middle line:84%
He died in 1859,
and he wrote a book

00:53:16.590 --> 00:53:19.410 align:middle line:84%
about mesmerism and
Andrew Jackson Davis,

00:53:19.410 --> 00:53:23.010 align:middle line:84%
defending Davis as an
authentic spirit channeler.

00:53:23.010 --> 00:53:26.850 align:middle line:84%
The notable thing about Davis
who is not read much today

00:53:26.850 --> 00:53:30.300 align:middle line:84%
and is not heard of
today is that he further

00:53:30.300 --> 00:53:34.770 align:middle line:84%
imbued Americans with this idea
that any ordinary person could

00:53:34.770 --> 00:53:36.930 align:middle line:84%
pierce the veil to
the divine, could

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:38.090 align:middle line:90%
play the part of prophet--

00:53:38.090 --> 00:53:39.450 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You didn't
need an intermediary--

00:53:39.450 --> 00:53:40.740 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: No intermediary.

00:53:40.740 --> 00:53:43.920 align:middle line:84%
And that was very American,
and it tapped American ideals.

00:53:43.920 --> 00:53:47.460 align:middle line:84%
The fact that Davis was
a cobbler's apprentice,

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:52.740 align:middle line:84%
was somebody who the newspapers
made fun of as a local yokel

00:53:52.740 --> 00:53:56.760 align:middle line:84%
from up the Hudson River, made
him endearing to Americans

00:53:56.760 --> 00:53:59.130 align:middle line:84%
because he was also playing
the part of prophet.

00:53:59.130 --> 00:54:01.830 align:middle line:84%
And it said to Americans--
it tapped into a very deep

00:54:01.830 --> 00:54:03.310 align:middle line:90%
American ideal--

00:54:03.310 --> 00:54:07.830 align:middle line:84%
which was that miracles,
prophecy, messages from God

00:54:07.830 --> 00:54:10.650 align:middle line:84%
weren't just restricted
to biblical antiquity,

00:54:10.650 --> 00:54:14.010 align:middle line:84%
but we could re-encounter them,
in Poughkeepsie, New York.

00:54:14.010 --> 00:54:14.930 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:54:14.930 --> 00:54:17.100 align:middle line:84%
And he ended up
writing this tome,

00:54:17.100 --> 00:54:20.460 align:middle line:84%
"The Principles of Nature,"
800 pages from his just

00:54:20.460 --> 00:54:21.870 align:middle line:90%
channeled works, right?

00:54:21.870 --> 00:54:22.670 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Yes.

00:54:22.670 --> 00:54:26.170 align:middle line:84%
And It is torturously-long,
very difficult to get through.

00:54:26.170 --> 00:54:30.450 align:middle line:84%
But it was a very
popular book in its day

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:34.380 align:middle line:84%
because people felt so excited
that this local kid could

00:54:34.380 --> 00:54:38.940 align:middle line:84%
possibly be a kind of
receptor for divine energies.

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:41.100 align:middle line:84%
And other Americans
began to ask, why not me?

00:54:41.100 --> 00:54:42.360 align:middle line:90%
Why not me?

00:54:42.360 --> 00:54:45.330 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, and one of
the people who witnessed him

00:54:45.330 --> 00:54:47.400 align:middle line:84%
and his work was-- he
was doing, apparently,

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:49.950 align:middle line:84%
a medical diagnosis at
the time, if I recall--

00:54:49.950 --> 00:54:51.600 align:middle line:90%
Henry Olcott Steel.

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:54.505 align:middle line:84%
And now we're getting into
just a really juicy story--

00:54:54.505 --> 00:54:56.255 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: This is
where it all happens--

00:54:56.255 --> 00:54:58.590 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --where he
and his relationship

00:54:58.590 --> 00:55:02.065 align:middle line:84%
with the wild
Russian woman begin.

00:55:02.065 --> 00:55:03.690 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about this
for a little bit.

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:05.356 align:middle line:84%
We might have to pick
it up again later,

00:55:05.356 --> 00:55:09.310 align:middle line:84%
but let's talk about who Henry
Olcott Steel was at the time.

00:55:09.310 --> 00:55:10.110 align:middle line:90%
>>HOROWITZ: Yeah.

00:55:10.110 --> 00:55:15.570 align:middle line:84%
This really opens the door to
the modern alternative virtual

00:55:15.570 --> 00:55:16.740 align:middle line:90%
culture.

00:55:16.740 --> 00:55:20.340 align:middle line:84%
Henry Steel Olcott was
a civil war Colonel

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:23.040 align:middle line:84%
who retired after
the war and thought

00:55:23.040 --> 00:55:26.370 align:middle line:84%
he was going to spend
his life toiling away

00:55:26.370 --> 00:55:28.620 align:middle line:90%
in a legal practice.

00:55:28.620 --> 00:55:31.140 align:middle line:84%
And, instead, he
developed an interest

00:55:31.140 --> 00:55:33.210 align:middle line:84%
in what was then
called spiritualism

00:55:33.210 --> 00:55:35.010 align:middle line:90%
or talking to the dead.

00:55:35.010 --> 00:55:38.080 align:middle line:84%
And this grew out of the
work of Andrew Jackson Davis,

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:38.960 align:middle line:90%
as you were alluding.

00:55:38.960 --> 00:55:40.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: He has witnessed
him doing a medical reading

00:55:40.480 --> 00:55:40.680 align:middle line:90%
on someone.

00:55:40.680 --> 00:55:43.055 align:middle line:84%
>>HOROWITZ: He had witnessed
him doing a medical reading,

00:55:43.055 --> 00:55:46.710 align:middle line:84%
and Davis also
imported from Europe

00:55:46.710 --> 00:55:50.790 align:middle line:84%
and reworked the term seance, or
sitting, and encouraged people

00:55:50.790 --> 00:55:53.700 align:middle line:84%
that if they wanted to
communicate with spirits

00:55:53.700 --> 00:55:55.230 align:middle line:84%
from the hidden
world, they should

00:55:55.230 --> 00:55:56.790 align:middle line:90%
form into seance circles.

00:55:56.790 --> 00:55:58.530 align:middle line:84%
And he gave very
precise instructions

00:55:58.530 --> 00:56:00.160 align:middle line:90%
as to how this could be done.

00:56:00.160 --> 00:56:02.280 align:middle line:84%
And also, again, in the
Burned-over district,

00:56:02.280 --> 00:56:04.800 align:middle line:84%
there were two young women
named the Fox sisters who

00:56:04.800 --> 00:56:06.510 align:middle line:84%
told their Methodist
parents that they

00:56:06.510 --> 00:56:10.040 align:middle line:84%
were channeling spirits from
the hidden world and so forth.

00:56:10.040 --> 00:56:14.720 align:middle line:84%
All this was unfolding in
the late 1840s, early 1850s.

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:18.890 align:middle line:84%
In fact, historians used to
call the 1840s the mad 40s.

00:56:18.890 --> 00:56:21.590 align:middle line:84%
We don't look back on it as
this particularly avant garde

00:56:21.590 --> 00:56:25.160 align:middle line:84%
era in American
life, but the 1840s

00:56:25.160 --> 00:56:27.770 align:middle line:84%
was a period of time when
America was at peace,

00:56:27.770 --> 00:56:31.190 align:middle line:84%
was prosperous, was expanding,
and people were experimenting.

00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:33.860 align:middle line:84%
So you have this
movement of spiritualism

00:56:33.860 --> 00:56:35.750 align:middle line:84%
where people are claiming
to talk to the dead

00:56:35.750 --> 00:56:37.640 align:middle line:84%
and receive spirit
transmissions.

00:56:37.640 --> 00:56:40.880 align:middle line:84%
Women are becoming
mediums, again,

00:56:40.880 --> 00:56:43.940 align:middle line:84%
filling a religious void,
filling a religious role.

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:47.870 align:middle line:84%
And Henry Steel Olcott who
was working as a lawyer,

00:56:47.870 --> 00:56:51.230 align:middle line:84%
as a journalist, as a
retired officer became very

00:56:51.230 --> 00:56:53.060 align:middle line:84%
interested in this,
began to write articles

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:54.350 align:middle line:90%
about this movement.

00:56:54.350 --> 00:56:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And he, in the early
1870s, is up in Vermont

00:56:58.940 --> 00:57:00.980 align:middle line:90%
visiting a haunted farmhouse.

00:57:00.980 --> 00:57:02.870 align:middle line:84%
And who does he
happen to meet but

00:57:02.870 --> 00:57:07.550 align:middle line:84%
this mysterious world-traveled
Russian noble woman named

00:57:07.550 --> 00:57:10.490 align:middle line:84%
Madame H.P. Blavatsky
who tells him

00:57:10.490 --> 00:57:13.520 align:middle line:84%
that she journeyed to
America because America

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:15.770 align:middle line:84%
is the cradle of
spiritualism and is

00:57:15.770 --> 00:57:18.200 align:middle line:84%
going to be the
birthplace of a revolution

00:57:18.200 --> 00:57:19.940 align:middle line:90%
in modern spirituality.

00:57:19.940 --> 00:57:22.220 align:middle line:84%
And the two get
together, and they start

00:57:22.220 --> 00:57:24.230 align:middle line:90%
writing and experimenting.

00:57:24.230 --> 00:57:27.770 align:middle line:84%
And they form a little society
first called The Miracle Club.

00:57:27.770 --> 00:57:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And then later, in
1875, they reform it

00:57:30.500 --> 00:57:34.640 align:middle line:84%
into a more formal group called
the Theosophical Society.

00:57:34.640 --> 00:57:38.840 align:middle line:84%
And Madame Blavatsky, his
partner and his co-explorer,

00:57:38.840 --> 00:57:43.010 align:middle line:84%
taught that all religions derive
from this ancient occult belief

00:57:43.010 --> 00:57:46.760 align:middle line:84%
system that we've lost sight
of, but that we can rediscover.

00:57:46.760 --> 00:57:49.820 align:middle line:84%
And that's really the birth
of the alternative spiritual

00:57:49.820 --> 00:57:51.400 align:middle line:90%
revolution.

00:57:51.400 --> 00:57:52.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Indeed.

00:57:52.340 --> 00:57:55.670 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot more to
say about Helena Blavatsky.

00:57:55.670 --> 00:57:58.310 align:middle line:84%
I think this is a really good
breaking point, which you just

00:57:58.310 --> 00:57:59.130 align:middle line:90%
said.

